<p>Considering that a good amount of staff is composed of those prominent writers themselves, I think it's an inherent problem in promoting users that create good content and have a satisfactory work ethic. When newer members proven to have decent heads on their shoulders are recruited, their article output takes a hit, and their efforts focus towards site work.</p>
<p>A focus on assisting the <em>recently</em> successful authors&#8212; particularly, users that prove they can write a compelling article&#8212; sounds like a good idea. Maybe a mentor type of system, since that's essentially what I went through when I initially joined the site. <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/crayne" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1346995); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1346995&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1495059392" alt="Crayne" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1346995)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/crayne" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1346995); return false;">Crayne</a></span> PMed me after a second deleted article, saying that he liked the idea, basically smoothing out all the kinks with it through line by line critique.</p>
<p>I'm a little wary about making this process a policy itself. Perhaps staff should simply promote greater communication between established writers and new writers that are willing to listen to feedback.</p>

							</div>

								
					
