					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/procyonlotor" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(778357); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=778357&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204957" alt="ProcyonLotor" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=778357)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/procyonlotor" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(778357); return false;" >ProcyonLotor</a></span> <span class="odate time_1495055894 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">17 May 2017 21:18</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2824618">
									

<p>My formal duties as a member of Licensing are primarily split between answering user questions and enforcing the license against violators, mostly just sending a message on the relevant sites, but occasionally we send a DMCA. This is essentially a pile of virtual paperwork and a bunch of scary promises made under penalty of perjury in order to deal with trenchant or particularly flagrant violations. These are always sent under someone's legal name and address, primarily mine because I was the one who cared the least about sharing it. On a bad day, something serious will come up and one of us will have to explain a particular intricacy of the Creative Commons License to staff at large.</p>
<p>Currently, we are also in the gradual process of assuming the responsibilities of the now-defunct Images Team, which is a slow, large system we're building, and the team is having a lot of internal policy discussions about how we'll handle it. It's as fascinating as it sounds.</p>
<p>There's a lot more informal duties as well- few staff things are done completely unilaterally, so people are always looking for input in SSSC. In addition, there's a bunch of things- summary deletions, regular deletions, bad crit, and improperly placed threads, et al, which are fairly teeny on their own but can add up if you let them.</p>
<p>For the actual workload, unless you're an admin, in which case you get only misery, it's essentially as much as you're willing to provide. There are no timesheets, and since we're not getting paid, no one will really fault you if you decide you're just not going to do much for a week.</p>
<p>As for the Cool Kids Club? Staff has never been as much of one as it has been accused of in the past, but there have been times where it was certainly <em>more</em> Cool Kid-y than at present. The addition of Junior Staff, some of whom have also been put in staff chat, has shaken up a lot of the settled old blood, thankfully.</p>

							</div>

								
					
